# Processing State Animation

When the UI enters a processing/loading state (AI thinking, agent activating, response streaming), the chat thread should slide up **16px** to create visual breathing room for the processing indicator. It slides back to its original position when processing ends.

## CSS Pattern

Apply `transform: translateY(-16px)` on the message thread container using a class toggle. Never use `margin` or `padding` changes for this — transforms don't affect layout and are GPU-accelerated.

```css
.messages {
  transform: translateY(0);
  transition: transform 0.28s ease-out;
}

.messages.proc-active {
  transform: translateY(-16px);
}
```

## Processing Row

The processing indicator row uses `max-height` + `opacity` to animate in/out without `display` toggling:

```css
.chat-processing-row {
  display: flex;
  max-height: 0;
  margin-bottom: 0;
  opacity: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  pointer-events: none;
  transition: max-height 0.28s ease-out, opacity 0.2s ease, margin-bottom 0.28s ease-out;
}

.chat-processing-row.visible {
  max-height: 36px;
  margin-bottom: 8px;
  opacity: 1;
  pointer-events: auto;
}
```

## JS Pattern

Toggle both classes together. After the collapse transition (300ms), scroll the container to its new bottom.

```js
function showProcessing() {
  processingRow.classList.add('visible');
  messagesEl.classList.add('proc-active');
  requestAnimationFrame(() => { chatContent.scrollTop = chatContent.scrollHeight; });
}

function hideProcessing() {
  processingRow.classList.remove('visible');
  messagesEl.classList.remove('proc-active');
  setTimeout(() => { chatContent.scrollTop = chatContent.scrollHeight; }, 300);
}
```

## Rules

- Always animate both the thread translate and the processing row together as a unit.
- Use `ease-out` timing — the movement should feel immediate and settle softly.
- 0.28s duration for spatial movement, 0.2s for opacity.
- Scroll to bottom with `requestAnimationFrame` when showing, and after a 300ms delay when hiding (to let the collapse finish first).
- If the processing cycles through a finite set of status words, auto-dismiss and call `hideProcessing()` at the end — do not loop forever.
